Statistical Distributions

Distributions form the backbone of Statistics. As a Data Scientist you are probably not going to be using these distributions directly too often, but they form the substrate beneath most of the techniques that you will be using regularly, so it’s prudent to know a bit about them. There are a myriad different distributions, but we’ll just be focusing on a few of them.

The menagerie of statistical distributions.

1 Bernoulli Trials & Binomial Distribution

A Bernoulli Trial is a simple experiment that has one of two possible outcomes: success or failure. Consider a coin flipping experiment.

sample(c("head", "tail"), 6, replace = TRUE)
[1] "head" "head" "tail" "tail" "head" "tail"

For a fair coin the probability of head and tail are both 50%. What about rolling dice? Suppose that you are playing a dice game which requires you to roll a 6 in order to win.

sample(c("win", "lose"), 8, replace = TRUE, prob = c(1, 5) / 6)
[1] "win"  "lose" "lose" "lose" "lose" "lose" "lose" "lose"

Here the probability of winning is 1/6, while the probability of losing is 5/6. Being a compulsive gambler, you’re not going to just play this game once. Hell no! You’ll keep on playing until either you lose your shirt or you walk away a zillionaire, right? Perhaps not. You do have a modicum of sense. So, suppose you decide to play the game 20 times. What is the probability that you win 5 of those games? This is a question best answered by the Binomial Distribution.

Let’s take a brief mathematical excursion. Suppose that every trial has a probability \(p\) of being successful. And, furthermore, that you engage in \(n\) trials. Then the probability that you are successful on \(k\) of those \(n\) trials is \[ P(X = k) = \binom{n}{k} p^k (1 - p)^{n - k} \] where \[ \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k! (n - k)!} \] is the binomial coefficient. Note that this is a discrete distribution: it describes the probability of a set of integer outcomes.

Returning to the dice game, we need to evaluate the above expressions with \(n = 20\), \(k = 5\) and \(p = 1/6\). We’ll start with the binomial coefficient.

factorial(20) / (factorial(5) * factorial(15))
[1] 15504

Fortunately R has a builtin function for this.

choose(20, 5)
[1] 15504

Now the rest is easy.

n = 20; k = 5; p = 1 / 6
choose(20, 5) * p^k * (1 - p)^(n - k)
[1] 0.1294103

It doesn’t seem very likely, but if you were a gambler, you’d probably take those odds.

We can also vary \(k\) to see what’s the most likely outcome of the 20 games. In the plot below the vertical lines indicate the probability of the corresponding value of \(k\), while the dashed curve is the cumulative probability (the sum of the individual probabilities up to that point).

It seems that we are most likely to win 3 of the 20 games. Does this make sense? The cumulative probability curve indicates that we are almost certain to win 8 or fewer games.

2 The Normal Distribution

The Normal Distribution (also known as “that damn bell-shaped curve”) is a well known landmark of Statistics. The Normal Distribution is a continuous distribution with parameters \(\mu\) (the mean) and \(\sigma\) (the standard deviation). Like all continuous distributions, the Normal Distribution is characterised by a Probability Density Function (PDF) \(P(X = x)\), and \(P(X = x) dx\) is the probability of a sample falling between \(x\) and \(x + dx\), where \(x\) ranges from \(-\infty\) to \(\infty\). The Cumulative Density Function (CDF) \(P(X \leq x)\) is the probability that a sample will not be greater than \(x\).

The plot below shows the PDF (solid line) and CDF (dashed line) for a Normal Distribution with \(\mu = 1\) and \(\sigma = 0.5\).

To visualise the effects of changing the mean and standard deviation, let’s have a look at similar curves for \(\mu = -1\) and \(\sigma = 1\).

We see that the centre of the distribution has shifted to -1 (the Normal Distribution is always peaked at the mean) and it’s broadened due to the larger standard deviation.

2.1 Standard or \(z\) Scores

The “standard” Normal Distribution (tautology much?) has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. It’s often helpful to standardise data. To do this we subtract the mean and divide through by the standard deviation: \[ \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}. \] You’ll see an example of how this works below.

3 The t Distribution

We’re going to gloss lightly over the t Distribution. You can think of it as a relative of the Normal Distribution which is applied when we have a limited (or finite) quantity of data. Equivalently, the Normal Distribution is the t Distribution in the limit of an infinite number of samples (or indeed the entire population).

The importance of the t Distribution becomes apparent when you consider that when calculating \(z\) scores for a sample, both the mean in the numerator and the standard deviation in the denominator are estimates. As a result these \(z\) scores are rather approximate. So, instead of using the Normal Distribution, we use the t Distribution to describe them.

The t Distribution has an additional parameter: the number of degrees of freedom, which corresponds approximately to the number of samples. In the plot below the t Distribution with 1, 3 and 10 degrees of freedom (solid curves, bottom to top) is compared to a standard Normal Distribution (dashed curve). It’s apparent that even for a moderately large sample size the t Distribution is very similar to the Normal Distribution. For smaller sample sizes the t Distribution has broader “tails”.

4 The Poisson & Exponential Distributions

The Poisson Distribution is another discrete probability distribution. It is generally used to model count data. For example, one might use the Poisson Distribution to describe the rate at which calls arrive at a call centre or the number of defects per unit length in a bale of material. Note that the distribution does not only relate to the temporal distribution of events, but it is most often thought of in this context.

If there are on average \(\lambda\) events per unit time, then the probability of their being \(k\) events in a particular interval is given by \[ P(X = k) = \frac{e^{-k} \lambda^k}{k!}. \]

Whereas the Poisson Distribution is used to model the number of events per unit time. The Exponential Distribution (which has the same parameter, \(\lambda\)) can be used to model the delay between successive events. The Exponential Distribution is a continuous distribution with PDF of \[ P(X = x) = \lambda e^{-\lambda x} \] where \(x\) runs from 0 to \(\infty\). The corresponding CDF is \[ P(X \leq x) = 1 - e^{\lambda x}. \]

Consider a queue at the Post Office, where people join the queue at an average rate of 120 per hour. What is the probability that between 105 and 135 people join the queue in any particular hour. Have a look at the CDF for \(\lambda = 120\) below.

We see that with probability 0.0907414 there will be fewer than 105 people and with probability 0.9193836 there will be fewer than 135 people. As a result there is a 0.8286422 probability that between 105 and 135 people will join the queue.

What about the rate at which people join the queue? We know that, on average, one person joins the queue every 30 seconds. The plot below shows the CDF for the Exponential Distribution.

We can see that in 90% of cases the interval is less than 69.0775528 seconds.

5 Distributions and Samples in R

For each of the distributions listed above (and a great many others! Have a look at ?Distributions.) R has a set of functions which allow us to interrogate various aspects of the distribution. These functions follow a uniform naming convention. We’re going to focus on the functions for the Normal Distribution, but the analogous functions for other distributions are easily located.

xkcd #221: Random Number. Probably not the best implementation.

5.1 The Normal Distribution

Values of the PDF are extracted using dnorm(), which takes as parameters the mean and standard deviation.

dnorm(c(-1, 0, 1), mean = 1, sd = 0.5)
[1] 0.0002676605 0.1079819330 0.7978845608

Values of the CDF are extracted using pnorm(), which takes as parameters the mean and standard deviation.

pnorm(c(-1, 0, 1), mean = 1, sd = 0.5)
[1] 3.167124e-05 2.275013e-02 5.000000e-01

There’s a theoretical quantile function as well.

qnorm(seq(0, 1, 0.25), mean = 1, sd = 0.5)
[1]      -Inf 0.6627551 1.0000000 1.3372449       Inf

This tells us that the lowest 25% of the distribution is smaller than 0.6627551.

Finally we are able to generate samples from a Normal Distribution using rnorm(). This is extremely useful when you’re doing a simulation.

(x = rnorm(10, mean = 1, sd = 0.5))
 [1]  1.3691624  1.2878907  0.8473058  1.7558906  1.1949216  0.6893797 -0.1073499  1.5624655
 [9]  0.9775332  0.9919049

If we generate a few thousand samples from the same distribution we can confirm that their distribution looks much like the underlying PDF.

Let’s return to our small sample and calculate the sample mean and standard deviation.

mean(x)
[1] 1.05691
sd(x)
[1] 0.5227174

If we standardise these data then the mean and standard deviation are changed to 0 and 1 respectively.

xnorm = (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
mean(xnorm)
[1] -2.636305e-17
sd(xnorm)
[1] 1

There’s a builtin R function scale() that can be used to standardise data.

5.2 Other Distributions

The analogous functions for the Binomial Distribution are dbinom(), pbinom(), qbinom() and rbinom(). For the Poisson Distribution they are dpois(), ppois(), qpoism() and rpois(). For the t Distribution we have dt(), pt(), qt() and rt(). Can you spot the pattern? The corresponding functions for the Exponential Distribution are documented at ?Exponential. There’s also a uniform distribution which is often used: have a look at ?Uniform.

5.3 Sampling from a Discrete Population

We’ve already seen sample() above. It’s used to generate random samples from a finite set of items. Suppose that you wanted to draw 10 numbers at random between 1 and 100.

sample(1:100, 10)
 [1] 47  8 20 64 93 79 30  7 10 32

This doesn’t just apply to numbers. The first argument to sample() can be any vector.

sample(c(letters, LETTERS), 10)
 [1] "j" "L" "J" "M" "c" "v" "r" "B" "o" "N"

6 Exercises

  1. In an agricultural experiment, a large uniform field was planted with a single variety of wheat. The field was divided into many plots (each plot being 200 m in length) and the yield (kg) of grain was measured for each plot. These plot yields followed approximately a normal distribution with mean 40 kg and standard deviation 3 kg. What percentage of the plot yields were:
  • 30 kg or more?
  • Between 35 and 40 kg?
  • Between 40 and 45 kg?
  • Less than 45 kg?
  1. You’re playing a simple game of dice, where success is rolling a 1 or a 2.
  • In 20 games, what is the probability exactly 5 successes?
  • In 20 games, is the probability of at least 5 successes?
  • Can you find a neat way to calculate the probability of between 3 and 6 successes in 20 games?
  1. Use dbinom() to calculate the probability of 5 successes in 20 games of dice. Can you find a neat way to calculate the probability of between 3 and 6 successes?
  2. Generate samples from a Poisson Distribution to simulate the Post Office queue (where people join at an average rate of 120 per hour). Calculate the sample mean and standard deviation. How do these compare with the theoretical mean and standard deviation?
  3. Without generating samples, calculate the median interval (in seconds) between people joining the Post Office queue.
  4. A casino game has a jackpot that pays out on average once every hour. Suppose that the jackpot was last triggered at 00:00.
  • What is the probability that the next jackpot will happen between 00:00 and 01:00?
  • What is the probability that the next jackpot will happen between 01:00 and 02:00?
  • If the jackpot does not happen between 00:00 and 01:00, what is the probability that it will happen between 01:00 and 02:00?
  1. Choose the statistical distribution that best represents each of the following situations, and explain why:
  • Grades in an introductory organic chemistry course.
  • The number of M&Ms of each colour in a pack.
  • The chance of drawing a card from the suit of Spades in a standard 52-card deck.
  • The number of emails received in a given hour during a workday.
  • The number of flight passengers at different gates in an airport.
